Alaska state health officials are reporting the second known novel orthopoxvirus case, aka “Alaskapox” in a resident of Fairbanks. In August, a woman presented with the following symptoms: A small grey lesion on her left upper arm, followed by erythema approximately 4 days later. She reported tender axillary adenopathy, shoulder pain, fatigue, and subjective fever at night. PCR testing performed by the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) identified it as a generic orthopoxvirus and sequencing determined it belonged to the lineage as the first ever case reported in a different Fairbanks woman in 2015. The patient had not traveled outside of Alaska for the past 3 years, but she did travel to Southcentral Alaska approximately 3 weeks before symptom onset. She reported that none of her family members or coworkers had any recent history of international travel. At the time of symptom onset, the patient lived with two cats. She reported that one of the cats captured and killed small mammals outside her residence, but the patient denied ever touching any of the small mammals. The patient also had regular contact with dogs owned by family members. amzn_assoc_placement = "adunit0";
